We updated forecasts at DT, w ecent positive US dynamics & an attractive valuation kept us Overweight. We raised our PT on VOD following a decent Q1. Elsewhere, we explored if Telefonica could explore a capital raise/consolidation with VOD Spain following a number of unconfirmed press articles.

Deutsche Telekom: Very attractive valuation given recent positive US dynamics - We update forecasts post results. While German competition is intense, we view the reaction to the Q2 results print (- 5%), implying a \(> - 15\%\) markdown to Telekom's German Telco business, as excessive. Q2 saw better revenue growth at TMUS, while M&A is accretive and shares have rebounded from June lows. DT will be a beneficiary of the One Big Beautiful Bill (US tax legislation), given its high US capital intensity (\$10bn pa). We now foresee lower US cash taxes. Iliad CEO rules out Telecom Italia Tie- Up - CEO of Iliad, Thomas Reynaud, confirmed that the group is no longer interested in a merger with TI following previous discussions on the matter. "There have been no discussions with Telecom Italia since early April, and they will not resume", said Reynaud following Iliad's Q2 results.

Martin Ebner takes \(3\%\) stake in Vodafone - Martin Ebner, a Swiss fund manager, has become one of Vodafone's largest shareholders after acquiring a \(3\%\) stake through his investment vehicle Patinex.

Our price target is derived from a SOTP. Each subsidiary is valued via a DCF, except T- Mobile US, which we value at our price target ( \(285 / share\) ). Key WACC/long- term growth assumptions as follows: German fixed \(7\% /0.5\%\) , German mobile \(6.5\% /1.5\%\) . Contingent liabilities include pension, restructuring and spectrum costs.
- TMUS top-line & EBITDA growth- Better-than-expected German revenue & EBITDAaL (share win, costs)- Further DT / TMUS buybacks- Potential M&A e.g. towers

- TMUS share price or US\\$ weakness- US mobile competition (cable)- Intensification of competition in Germany (1&1)- Higher spectrum costs / taxes- Wholesale German revenue loss & lower retail EBITDA via FTTH new entrants- More elevated FTTH capex

We use a Sum- of- the- Parts to reach our Vodafone price target of 95p, valuing each subsidiary via a DCF. We assume a WACC of 6.5- 8.0% across Vodafone Europe, while our terminal growth rates are 0.0- 1.5%. Associates include Australia, towers etc. Contingent liabilities include Common Functions, spectrum costs and re- structuring. Our terminal Group EBITDA margin is 30% (25a: 29.2%), while our terminal Group capex/sales is 17.1% (25a: 18.3%).

- Better-than-expected bounce in revenues (price rises, 5G / Unlimited)- Stronger Group EBITDAaL growth, cost cuts- German turnaround & market recovery- Better UK EBITDAaL via merger- Telco industry M&A- Further portfolio / asset sales
- New wave of Challenger discounting- Sustained EBITDAaL declines in Germany- Failure to deliver UK merger synergies- Cycle of higher wireless capex (5G, "rip & replace")
